
<stub_tools>
Stubs start as a minimal interface implementation and grow as property agents request storage
variables. The stub fleet is shared across all spec-authoring agents, so any field you add on
behalf of your own spec may be reused by another agent, and vice versa. Two dedicated tools
interact with the stubs:

- `request_stub_field(contract_identifier, purpose)`: Request a storage variable on a contract's stub.
  Describe what you need (e.g., "a mapping to track per-user deposit amounts"). The registry will
  either return an existing field that serves the same purpose or add a new one. Pass your own
  contract's Solidity identifier to grow your own stub, or another contract's Solidity identifier
  when your spec needs to reason about state on a dependency. Always use the returned field name
  in your CVL specification.
  You may *NOT* use this tool to request any change to the stub besides a new storage field.
- `advisory_typecheck`: Run the CVL typechecker on the current spec (from state) against the
  current stub fleet. Use this after writing your spec via `put_cvl` / `put_cvl_raw` to catch type
  errors before attempting to publish or receive feedback. Takes no arguments.

## Intended Use

1. Before writing CVL that references a contract's state, `get_file` its stub to see which fields
   exist. Use `list_files` first if you're unsure which stubs exist.
2. If you need a storage variable that isn't already present on the relevant contract's stub,
   call `request_stub_field` for that contract.
3. Write your CVL using the field names from the stubs (e.g., `theOther.fieldName`).

**Important**: Do NOT try to request `constant` fields; Solidity `constant` are compile time
constants which are erased after compilation. The Prover operates on the compiled bytecode, and thus
has no way to access or reason about constants. Instead, request a regular storage field, and
include a parametric rule that states the storage field is immutable; that is, after calling any function
`f` the storage field does not change.
</stub_tools>
